title: For Sale:  Remington 12 gauge Shotgun Magazine Extension +1 TacCap 870 1100 with Detent Type Lug
postcontent: Seller Stock #: XMTC NO MAGAZINE SALES INTO NEW YORK CITY. CONNECTICUT RESIDENTS MUST FURNISH US A COPY OF YOUR CT ELIGIBILITY PERMIT OR AMMUNITION CERTIFICATE. Here is one of the best shotgun accessories on the market, but not the best known. This part replaces a standard magazine cap on older model Remingtons, or current production 870P and recent production 1100P Police Shotguns. This is the Tac-Cap Magazine Cap for above mentioned Remington 12 gauge Shotguns. It is simple to install; a person carefully removes the magazine cap from your Remington, holding it so that the spring doesn’t launch it; then remove the magazine spring retainer if any with a similarly careful approach, depress the spring back into the magazine tube, and screw on the Tac-Cap until you hear it ratchet into place. Overall length is only 2 1/2 inches. Manufacturer and warrantor is Precision Gun Specialties from Sheridan, MI. Construction is lightweight aluminum alloy, with checkered nurling and end cross cuts. Weight is only 1 1/2 ounces, less than the factory cap and retainer. It will fit old model Remington 12 gauge pump and semi auto shotgun manufactured prior to 1986 with no modification, including models Sportsman 12 pump and auto; 870 Wingmaster, 870 Police, and the venerable 1100. This tube extension will readily fit standard old model Remington 12 gauge shotguns with detent balls embedded into their barrel lugs; and whose magazine tubes hold 4 rounds of 2 3/4 inch shells. This replacement cap will bring magazine tube capacity up from 4 to 5 each 2 3/4 inch shells, and give a Remington a 5+1 capacity instead of 4 + 1 on 2 3/4 inch. It will yield similar results on 3 inch shells, from 3+1 up to 4+1, but very few of the older Remingtons were even made for 3 inch shells. It will not fit a Model 11, or a 31, or a 48, or a 58. Remington Shotguns with dimpled magazine tubes and magazine spring retainers that rotate into place must have their dimples removed and their main tubes modified. See the photos for the difference. The newer manufactured post 1985, 870s and 11-87s will require modification to their magazine tubes, since there are dimples inside the new shotguns' tubes that hold the spring retainer in place. The way we do it is simply Dremel down the two dimples and make sure the inside of the tube is smooth so that the shells will move along smoothly in the tube. Once a person does that, he cannot go back to the old shorter style; it permanently modifies the magazine tube of the shotgun itself. Carrying more than two shells in a magazine tube for hunting Federal status Migratory birds – doves, ducks, and crows – is a violation of federal law. In some states more than two shells hunting anything is a violation of state law. Installing one of these on an imported shotgun is also a violation of Federal Law if it makes the magazine capable of holding more than 5 shells. Some guy in Harris county has what is obviously an illegally modified Saiga (Russian sporterized AK variant in 7.62x39) that he's trying to sell here (and it's my buisness because it draws negative heat on an otherwise excellent site, and gun ownership in general) . 
 I sent him a message yesterday with a very polite heads-up, and he's ignored it. This rifle clearly fails to conform to usc922r, which requires a certain number of US-made parts to replace the foreign-made parts, before converting to accept high capacity magazines (this is very well known and widely discussed on nearly every gun forum, for years now). 
 This rifle obviously hasn't had any trigger replacement, or stock replacement, and has a foreign 30-rd mag installed.
His price is well below market value, so I'm personally very suspicious, and would be very reluctant to take possesion of it.
Though it's probably unlikely, I wouldn't be surprised if it was some kind of sting operation. Coincidentally, there was a virtually identical rifle out of Atlanta last week, on TheOutdoorsTrader. I mentioned it to that guy also, and he basically flipped me off, and now the rifle's gone, but then one just like it appears down here.
Take it for what it's worth.
That is all.
